than either coal or oil.

00:16:49.140 --> 00:16:53.460
But basically by 1914 and according

00:16:53.460 --> 00:16:56.990
to this mini chronograph I found
here at the Library of Congress,

00:16:56.990 --> 00:17:01.820
around 75% of the Russian rail
network was powered by coal,

00:17:01.820 --> 00:17:06.650
around 10% by oil and there's a
way to power locomotives using oil,

00:17:06.650 --> 00:17:10.110
and then approximately
5 to 10% by wood.

00:17:10.110 --> 00:17:14.080
But all of the main rail
connections in European Russia,

00:17:14.080 --> 00:17:19.120
the major rail routes use coal
or oil, wood was used only

00:17:19.120 --> 00:17:22.530
on local lines or in
Siberia in particular

00:17:22.530 --> 00:17:25.680
because there was a
lot of wood in Siberia.

00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:28.710 position:56%
And so one of the things I want to
talk about just getting back briefly

00:17:28.710 --> 00:17:32.810
to this oil be transported
from Baku up to the mouth

00:17:32.810 --> 00:17:38.290
of the Volga River is that
initially when [inaudible] came

00:17:38.290 --> 00:17:41.600
to the Volga River it used
wood, wood was the source.

00:17:41.600 --> 00:17:49.650 position:56%
It was only after 1880 that you had
use of oil to power the Volga fleet.

00:17:49.650 --> 00:17:52.020
And as you see the
development of the Volga fleet,

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:54.770
especially after 1890
and into the beginning

00:17:54.770 --> 00:17:59.460
of the 20th century it is
making leaps and bounds in terms

00:17:59.460 --> 00:18:03.870
of how energy-efficient it is
and how much cargo it can carry.

00:18:03.870 --> 00:18:08.320
So for instance in 1914 there
are over 200 million poods

00:18:08.320 --> 00:18:12.600
of various grains that
were conveyed up the Volga.

00:18:12.600 --> 00:18:16.810
And basically in 1903 Rudolf
Diesel licensed the diesel engine

00:18:16.810 --> 00:18:18.950
to the Nobel family.

00:18:18.950 --> 00:18:24.440
And you have the initial
construction of diesel tugboats.

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:31.170 position:56%
Some of these diesel tugboats on the
Volga could carry as much on barges

00:18:31.170 --> 00:18:37.860
at one time, just one diesel engine
tugboat carrying several large

00:18:37.860 --> 00:18:41.840
barges, 500,000 poods of grain.

00:18:41.840 --> 00:18:46.470
That would be the equivalent
of 500 rail cars of grain.

00:18:46.470 --> 00:18:50.930
There is a recognition from a
lot of material both primary

00:18:50.930 --> 00:18:56.120
and secondary before the revolution
during 1917 and afterwards

00:18:56.120 --> 00:19:00.170
that one railcar, standard
Russian railcar,

00:19:00.170 --> 00:19:04.810
could carry around a thousand poods
of grain, which is 36,000 pounds

00:19:04.810 --> 00:19:08.470
so approximately 18 tons.

00:19:08.470 --> 00:19:13.430
So you had a tremendous increase
in the intensity and efficiency

00:19:13.430 --> 00:19:18.310
of the Volga commercial fleet in
terms of delivering many things.

00:19:18.310 --> 00:19:23.390
Not just grain, but all kinds of
building supplies, raw materials,

00:19:23.390 --> 00:19:27.370
salt, many other things that
were needed by the economy.

00:19:27.370 --> 00:19:34.720
And what we'll see is that by 1920
the Soviet Regime had been going

00:19:34.720 --> 00:19:40.350
for an entire full-year, for all of
1919 and really a good part of 1918

00:19:40.350 --> 00:19:46.050
as well, would have access to
any sources of coal or oil.

00:19:46.050 --> 00:19:51.580 position:56%
And so I think one of the things
that has really not been appreciated

00:19:51.580 --> 00:19:55.340
in history of what was going
during the Civil War period was

00:19:55.340 --> 00:19:58.040
that the economy really became
entirely dependent on wood.

00:19:58.040 --> 00:20:06.270
Wood is a much more inefficient
source of energy than oil or coal.

00:20:06.270 --> 00:20:12.420
It is very hard to use wood as
the main source for locomotives

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:14.810
and that was the underlying
reason why there was

00:20:14.810 --> 00:20:21.080
such a large transport crisis
in the Soviet control territory

00:20:21.080 --> 00:20:24.460
in European Russia by 1920.

00:20:24.460 --> 00:20:27.290
And in fact, what I found in
all of these sources and it's --

00:20:27.290 --> 00:20:32.180
I'm going to make an argument
people may want to swat me for it,

00:20:32.180 --> 00:20:35.090
but I'm going to make an argument
that [inaudible] Izvestia are very,

00:20:35.090 --> 00:20:36.390
very important sources

00:20:36.390 --> 00:20:38.860
for understanding what
was going on at the time.

00:20:38.860 --> 00:20:40.570
And not only in [inaudible]
Izvestia,

00:20:40.570 --> 00:20:44.230
but all of the primary
source materials I found here

00:20:44.230 --> 00:20:49.860
at the Library of Congress they
always talk about the use of wood

00:20:49.860 --> 00:20:52.570
and they convert it
to what they believed

00:20:52.570 --> 00:20:54.700
and they had good scientific
basis for this,

00:20:54.700 --> 00:20:56.250
they may be approximations.

00:20:56.250 --> 00:20:59.930
What was the equivalent energy
use of either coal or oil

00:20:59.930 --> 00:21:02.970
and especially dealing
with railroads they talk

00:21:02.970 --> 00:21:05.240
about the equivalent
wood used and what

00:21:05.240 --> 00:21:08.610 position:56%
that would have amounted to in coal.

00:21:08.610 --> 00:21:11.160
And so I'm also going to explain

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:18.920
in April 1920 the local Azeri
government Baku which was supported

00:21:18.920 --> 00:21:23.830
by the British, the Red Army
eventually captured Baku

00:21:23.830 --> 00:21:26.690
in late April 1920.

00:21:26.690 --> 00:21:29.940
And all of a sudden there
is a change in the picture.

00:21:29.940 --> 00:21:36.060 position:56%
A country that has not had access to
oil suddenly has some access to oil.

00:21:36.060 --> 00:21:42.120 position:56%
It's limited amounts, but it changes
the whole economic perspective

00:21:42.120 --> 00:21:44.780
of what is going on.

00:21:44.780 --> 00:21:47.510
And it doesn't mean that
everything changes immediately,

00:21:47.510 --> 00:21:51.010
in fact it doesn't and I will
skip ahead and say for instance,

00:21:51.010 --> 00:21:54.200
that at least through the
end of 1920, well into 1921

00:21:54.200 --> 00:21:58.190
and beyond wood remained
the single largest source

00:21:58.190 --> 00:22:01.830
for powering the Russian
rail network.

00:22:01.830 --> 00:22:06.770
And that's what the Soviet Regime
had to deal with was this gathering

00:22:06.770 --> 00:22:10.600
of wood, the transporting of
wood and getting this wood

00:22:10.600 --> 00:22:15.360
to local rail depots,
local rail lines.

00:22:15.360 --> 00:22:18.210
Procuring wood is a very, very
difficult thing in large amounts.

00:22:18.210 --> 00:22:21.080
It has to be chopped, it
has to best transported.

00:22:21.080 --> 00:22:24.840
There are two ways really of
transporting wood in large volumes

00:22:24.840 --> 00:22:27.070
of the type that a real
network would need.

00:22:27.070 --> 00:22:29.830
You either need to send
it down rivers or you have

00:22:29.830 --> 00:22:31.600
to have peasants haul it.

00:22:31.600 --> 00:22:35.240
And so one of the main things
that peasants did for the regime

00:22:35.240 --> 00:22:40.330
and basically was a form of labor
conscription was hauling wood

00:22:40.330 --> 00:22:43.580
so that the rail system could work.

00:22:43.580 --> 00:22:48.120
The other way to do it if you
send it downriver has its downside

00:22:48.120 --> 00:22:50.730
and this is discussed
a tremendous amount

00:22:50.730 --> 00:22:54.460
in the primary source materials
is the wood has a certain amount

00:22:54.460 --> 00:22:59.540
of humidity in that it is that
much more difficult to burn

00:22:59.540 --> 00:23:01.620
in the boiler of a locomotive.

00:23:01.620 --> 00:23:05.570 position:56%
And there are numerous references to
the fact that boilers either explode

00:23:05.570 --> 00:23:10.500
or break because the wood that is
being put into them is too humid.

00:23:10.500 --> 00:23:13.780
These are kind of what may
sound like small details,

00:23:13.780 --> 00:23:17.560
but when you look at them from
a larger picture and realize

00:23:17.560 --> 00:23:19.600
that wood was the main source

00:23:19.600 --> 00:23:26.800
for the Russian rai network really
beginning the 1918 you get a sense

00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:29.010
of what people were really
dealing with in trying

00:23:29.010 --> 00:23:31.550
to make this transport system work.

00:23:31.550 --> 00:23:37.600
So I wanted to just -- I've given
a handout and in in the handout,

00:23:37.600 --> 00:23:42.230
one of the handouts I talked
about and I'm just going

00:23:42.230 --> 00:23:43.790
to summarize it quickly here

00:23:43.790 --> 00:23:50.780
if I can find the right page here
what are the energy equivalents

00:23:50.780 --> 00:23:55.770
