at least 5 or 600 people attending,
had key speeches by Alexei Rykov,

00:33:00.950 --> 00:33:04.300
Trotsky I'm sure you've
heard of, some other people.

00:33:04.300 --> 00:33:08.000
And it says on the out of
this, it's only 34 pages,

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:13.150
this was copy forwarded
by American July 30, 1920,

00:33:13.150 --> 00:33:14.450
that's what's on the cover here.

00:33:14.450 --> 00:33:17.260
This was a meeting that
happened approximately five

00:33:17.260 --> 00:33:20.210
and a half months earlier
on January 25th.

00:33:20.210 --> 00:33:25.480
And basically I've never seen a
meeting or a speech like this,

00:33:25.480 --> 00:33:27.260
although there was a lot

00:33:27.260 --> 00:33:31.170
of very open talk while
[inaudible] were censored,

00:33:31.170 --> 00:33:34.090
it is remarkable how
much openness there was

00:33:34.090 --> 00:33:35.690
and what they talked about.

00:33:35.690 --> 00:33:40.650
But this speech mainly by
Alexei Rykov who's head

00:33:40.650 --> 00:33:45.420
of the Supreme Council of National
Economy he speaks as someone

00:33:45.420 --> 00:33:49.950 position:56%
who believes in the communist
regime and in the communist project.

00:33:49.950 --> 00:33:54.010
But it's really couched in
terms that anyone who believes

00:33:54.010 --> 00:33:56.410
in the market economy of
any kind, whether capitalist

00:33:56.410 --> 00:33:58.320
or whatever wouldn't
have given this speech.

00:33:58.320 --> 00:34:04.000
And what Rykov says in this speech
is that the economy is destroyed.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:07.960
And then he proceeds to give a
lot of key data points for that.

00:34:07.960 --> 00:34:09.520
One of the things that I've read,

00:34:09.520 --> 00:34:13.120
kind of one of the most famous
histories of the Civil War period

00:34:13.120 --> 00:34:17.410
by Edward Carr talks in
general terms about the fact

00:34:17.410 --> 00:34:24.250
that the economy declined by two
thirds between 1917 and 1923.

00:34:24.250 --> 00:34:27.270
And there's a general
recognition by all historians

00:34:27.270 --> 00:34:31.000
that what the revolution
and Civil War did

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:34.720
to Soviet Russia economically
was a disaster,

00:34:34.720 --> 00:34:37.020
it was basically a
complete collapse.

00:34:37.020 --> 00:34:40.830
But Rykov really puts some
meat on the bones of this

00:34:40.830 --> 00:34:42.780
that I think is unique and
makes that [inaudible].

00:34:42.780 --> 00:34:51.530
So one of the things he says is he
says that because of the collapse

00:34:51.530 --> 00:34:55.990
of the transport system and then
Trotsky also supports him on this

00:34:55.990 --> 00:34:58.990
and in some important
articles contributes

00:34:58.990 --> 00:35:04.010
to [inaudible] is Rykov
says we're here in Moscow,

00:35:04.010 --> 00:35:09.800 position:56%
the Soviet Regime kind of controls
the central European part of Russia.

00:35:09.800 --> 00:35:15.610
But he says that we have no
contact with [inaudible].

00:35:15.610 --> 00:35:18.700
We don't have enough trains, we
can't make them work well enough

00:35:18.700 --> 00:35:22.340
and the [inaudible] is
basically a separate economy,

00:35:22.340 --> 00:35:23.820
it's been largely destroyed

00:35:23.820 --> 00:35:27.240
or to a very large extent
destroyed during the Civil War.

00:35:27.240 --> 00:35:32.610
But if we wanted to import iron
ore from the [inaudible] to Moscow

00:35:32.610 --> 00:35:37.600 position:56%
and make metal Moscow and in Saint
Petersburg factories right now given

00:35:37.600 --> 00:35:41.710
the amount of trains and transport
capacity we have it would take us

00:35:41.710 --> 00:35:44.900
many decades to just
get that started.

00:35:44.900 --> 00:35:47.560
And then he says, there was
a very large textile industry

00:35:47.560 --> 00:35:49.670
in Russia before the revolution.

00:35:49.670 --> 00:35:54.180
He said if we wanted to take the
cotton from Uzbekistan and bring it

00:35:54.180 --> 00:35:56.710
to Moscow and Saint Petersburg
and there were large numbers

00:35:56.710 --> 00:36:01.920
of unemployed textile workers he
said that would take 20 years.

00:36:01.920 --> 00:36:06.360 position:56%
So what the discussion about in this
long speech by Rykov and he talks

00:36:06.360 --> 00:36:08.910
about the destruction of
national wealth almost

00:36:08.910 --> 00:36:10.760
as if he was a market economist.

00:36:10.760 --> 00:36:13.800
There are there other
references and other things.

00:36:13.800 --> 00:36:16.520
But what he says is there's
a tremendous destruction

00:36:16.520 --> 00:36:19.150
of national wealth
here and the fact is

00:36:19.150 --> 00:36:23.210
that the transport system is
not something that allows us

00:36:23.210 --> 00:36:26.250
to recreate this whole
national economy

00:36:26.250 --> 00:36:28.850
that existed before World War 1

00:36:28.850 --> 00:36:31.640
and that clearly had suffered
a lot during the course

00:36:31.640 --> 00:36:32.990
of World War 1 as well.

00:36:32.990 --> 00:36:36.050
I don't want to minimize
the importance of that.

00:36:36.050 --> 00:36:39.900
And so what he's saying is we don't
have the trains to bring the grain

00:36:39.900 --> 00:36:42.280
from the Volga region
to central Russia.

00:36:42.280 --> 00:36:47.020
These are basically grain deficit
areas, they don't grow enough grain

00:36:47.020 --> 00:36:49.720
to feed the local population.

00:36:49.720 --> 00:36:55.670
We don't have the trains to bring
the coal from Eastern Ukraine

00:36:55.670 --> 00:36:58.450
to make our locomotives work.

00:36:58.450 --> 00:37:03.240
And so the question is at the
beginning of 1920, is it possible

00:37:03.240 --> 00:37:06.540
to basically stitch together the
whole country, is it possible.

00:37:06.540 --> 00:37:10.590
And they really want to rule out
is it possible at all and then B,

00:37:10.590 --> 00:37:14.800
if it is possible how do we do it.

00:37:14.800 --> 00:37:16.580
And one of the interesting things

00:37:16.580 --> 00:37:19.100
that Rykov cites is
he says specifically

00:37:19.100 --> 00:37:24.330 position:56%
and I'm not an economist, I'm not
here to get into economic statistics

00:37:24.330 --> 00:37:27.440
or how much did the economy
decline I'm much more interested

00:37:27.440 --> 00:37:29.710
in the qualitative
aspects of what was going

00:37:29.710 --> 00:37:32.930
on with some important
quantitative measurements.

00:37:32.930 --> 00:37:35.080
But Rykov does cite the fact

00:37:35.080 --> 00:37:37.530
that the economy has
declined by two thirds.

00:37:37.530 --> 00:37:39.630
He does use that number.

00:37:39.630 --> 00:37:42.730
And then he cites another
very scary statistic,

00:37:42.730 --> 00:37:46.050
he says that because we
don't have access to oil,

00:37:46.050 --> 00:37:50.300
this is in early 1920, we
lack all the lubricants

00:37:50.300 --> 00:37:54.480 position:56%
that we need to do railroad repairs.

00:37:54.480 --> 00:37:59.960
We can't feed the workers who
would be fixing locomotives

00:37:59.960 --> 00:38:02.380
because they've run
away to the countryside,

00:38:02.380 --> 00:38:05.010
that's where the food is,
there's no real food in Moscow

00:38:05.010 --> 00:38:08.390
because trains can't bring it
there in sufficient quantities.

00:38:08.390 --> 00:38:11.310
And so it's kind of a Rubik's cube
how do you start putting this all

00:38:11.310 --> 00:38:12.980
back together.

00:38:12.980 --> 00:38:16.910
And he cites in addition to the
constraints that I mentioned

00:38:16.910 --> 00:38:20.750
about how much wood do you need
to make things move and, you know,

00:38:20.750 --> 00:38:23.990
you need one railcar of
wood just to move one

00:38:23.990 --> 00:38:28.000
of these trains a 100
verst or 66 miles.

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:31.700
But what happens is that because
there's been no ongoing repairs

00:38:31.700 --> 00:38:34.890
of locomotives for many years now
and it started to really decline

00:38:34.890 --> 00:38:39.530
in 1914, he cites the
fact that he believes

00:38:39.530 --> 00:38:41.570
and there are no exact
numbers it's a period

00:38:41.570 --> 00:38:44.210 position:56%
of really tremendous economic chaos.

00:38:44.210 --> 00:38:49.140
He says we believe at this
point we have 3,800 locomotives

00:38:49.140 --> 00:38:50.440
that are operational.

00:38:50.440 --> 00:38:53.550
They may not be in good repair,
but at least they're moving.

00:38:53.550 --> 00:38:57.800
They may need repairs,
but we're down to 3,800.

00:38:57.800 --> 00:39:02.630
The number in 1914 of locomotives
that were available was 20,000.

00:39:02.630 --> 00:39:05.530
And there was a lot of information

00:39:05.530 --> 00:39:08.780
in all these primary resource
materials, what were the number

00:39:08.780 --> 00:39:15.230
of locomotives that were
produced in 1919, it was 149.

00:39:15.230 --> 00:39:18.860
In the years before the revolution
and there are a lot of statistics

00:39:18.860 --> 00:39:22.520
in these Soviet journals from
1920 that are unique here

00:39:22.520 --> 00:39:25.600
at the Library I believe
in terms of complete set,

00:39:25.600 --> 00:39:31.420
the economy was building up a
thousand locomotives a year.

00:39:31.420 --> 00:39:35.480
And so there was a key article in
Pravda that raises the question,

00:39:35.480 --> 00:39:39.270
it's a logical question I haven't
seen it addressed anyplace else,

00:39:39.270 --> 00:39:44.240
at what point do we get to a number
of locomotives as they're declining

00:39:44.240 --> 00:39:48.290
where we can't really
effectively move anything.

00:39:48.290 --> 00:39:51.410
It may be that the [inaudible]
are a separate economy themselves,

00:39:51.410 --> 00:39:56.630
the Ukraine is a separate economy,
there's a wish to bring grain

00:39:56.630 --> 00:39:59.470
from Siberia because Western
Siberia is actually a net grain

00:39:59.470 --> 00:40:00.770
producing area.

00:40:00.770 --> 00:40:03.490
That comes up later in the 20's
I don't want to get into it

00:40:03.490 --> 00:40:06.310
when Stalin wants to get more grain
he goes after the [inaudible],

00:40:06.310 --> 00:40:08.420
it's called the [inaudible]
Siberian method.

00:40:08.420 --> 00:40:11.790
He's after extra grain in the
[inaudible] and in Western Siberia.

00:40:11.790 --> 00:40:15.820
And Western Siberia
probably had a grain surplus

00:40:15.820 --> 00:40:18.110
of around 100 million poods a year.

00:40:18.110 --> 00:40:20.820
Lenin is very interested
in that let me assure you.

00:40:20.820 --> 00:40:23.010
But the problem is even if
they could get their hands

00:40:23.010 --> 00:40:26.290
on it how do you transport this

00:40:26.290 --> 00:40:30.980
when one railcar will
take you 66 miles okay.

00:40:30.980 --> 00:40:34.700
That's assuming you have
the wood to begin with.

00:40:34.700 --> 00:40:37.360
So what I found in this key article

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:41.680
in Pravda is the question is asked
specifically, what's the number

00:40:41.680 --> 00:40:45.090
where the system no longer
works at all, it's very much

00:40:45.090 --> 00:40:46.820
on the verge of collapse.

00:40:46.820 --> 00:40:49.560 position:56%
And a very interesting fellow writes
an article in Pravda and says,

00:40:49.560 --> 00:40:54.690 position:56%
if we get to 2,500 it's over, we
shouldn't even start trying anymore,

00:40:54.690 --> 00:40:58.630 position:56%
there's going to be no more economy,
you know, there won't be a regime.

00:40:58.630 --> 00:41:03.900 position:56%
And there's a lot of open discussion
about can the regime survive.

00:41:03.900 --> 00:41:07.570
The word in Russian [foreign
language] is used throughout these

00:41:07.570 --> 00:41:09.170
primary source documents.

00:41:09.170 --> 00:41:13.590
On a couple of occasions Lenin
uses it, it's rare, but he uses it.

00:41:13.590 --> 00:41:17.140
He even makes reference to the way
things were at the end of 1919,

00:41:17.140 --> 00:41:20.550
the regime cannot continue
that way he says it

00:41:20.550 --> 00:41:26.660
in a key speech that's included
in his collective works.

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:33.350
So what Rykov explains at this key
meeting at the American Consulate

00:41:33.350 --> 00:41:37.140
in [inaudible] is that he
thinks they have around 3,800,

00:41:37.140 --> 00:41:39.420
2,500 seems to be kind
of the barrier

00:41:39.420 --> 00:41:42.130
where you can just forget about it.

00:41:42.130 --> 00:41:47.710 position:56%
And the concern is is that with each
passing month there are 200 less

00:41:47.710 --> 00:41:49.450
working locomotives every month.

00:41:49.450 --> 00:41:52.850
So they start doing projections
that if it keeps going this way

00:41:52.850 --> 00:41:56.350
by the end of 1920 there's
nothing more to talk about.

00:41:56.350 --> 00:41:58.370
That's why there are
these discussions

00:41:58.370 --> 00:42:02.190
about it's a fight for survival.

00:42:02.190 --> 00:42:04.880
They use the word [foreign
language] in Russian fight,

00:42:04.880 --> 00:42:09.300
they use the word [foreign
language] survival.

00:42:09.300 --> 00:42:13.510
And so really what happens and
I know time is short here is

00:42:13.510 --> 00:42:16.720
that Trotsky takes the lead,
Trotsky is really the key person

00:42:16.720 --> 00:42:19.240
in 1920 other than Lenin.

00:42:19.240 --> 00:42:23.720
And Trotsky comes up with a plan
how do we start repairing these

00:42:23.720 --> 00:42:26.430
locomotives, how do we do that.

00:42:26.430 --> 00:42:30.420
And what you see is there
is a period of late,

00:42:30.420 --> 00:42:33.330
I know this sounds very
specific, but there's a period

00:42:33.330 --> 00:42:38.660
in late February 1920 until
approximately the first weeks

00:42:38.660 --> 00:42:42.730
of April where everyone is
questioning whether the regime

00:42:42.730 --> 00:42:44.250
will survive.

00:42:44.250 --> 00:42:49.370
And it's in exactly that
time that Lenin, Trotsky,

00:42:49.370 --> 00:42:53.750
the whole senior Bolshevik
leadership makes a very concerted

00:42:53.750 --> 00:42:59.200 position:56%
effort to turn this around and I
have some statistics in the handbook

00:42:59.200 --> 00:43:01.160
and it starts to show
that this decline

00:43:01.160 --> 00:43:06.310
of approximately 200
locomotives a month is staunched,

00:43:06.310 --> 00:43:07.680
they're just starting to hold even.

00:43:07.680 --> 00:43:13.600
And then as you get into summer
1920 Trotsky as commissar

00:43:13.600 --> 00:43:16.760
of transport starts to
really turn this around.

00:43:16.760 --> 00:43:20.020
Not in a big way it doesn't get
them a lot of breathing room,

00:43:20.020 --> 00:43:22.930
but the fact that the regime
is on life support it's

00:43:22.930 --> 00:43:29.290
on the precedence that
comes to an end.

00:43:29.290 --> 00:43:33.630
They're not making the rail system
as a whole work a whole lot better,

00:43:33.630 --> 00:43:37.310
but there's no longer a sense
our necks are on the block

00:43:37.310 --> 00:43:39.410
that is just not the case.

00:43:39.410 --> 00:43:41.140
So I'm running a little
short on time.

00:43:41.140 --> 00:43:43.910
I wanted to say a couple
things about Trotsky.

00:43:43.910 --> 00:43:50.800
The Library here has
Trotsky's complete works

00:43:50.800 --> 00:43:54.510
or close approximation
to them were published.

00:43:54.510 --> 00:43:57.630
The Library has a complete,
has all of the volumes.

00:43:57.630 --> 00:44:00.240
Volume 15, which I
know may sound esoteric

00:44:00.240 --> 00:44:03.410
that covers everything
he did in 1920.

00:44:03.410 --> 00:44:07.030
And basically what Trotsky did
in late May 1920 as commissar

00:44:07.030 --> 00:44:10.560
of transport was he issued
what became a famous order,

00:44:10.560 --> 00:44:13.890
it was called order number 1042.

00:44:13.890 --> 00:44:19.010
And that was an industrial
plan to produce spare parts

00:44:19.010 --> 00:44:22.200
so that these locomotives
could be fixed.

00:44:22.200 --> 00:44:24.780
And in the meantime, they're
starting to get a little trickle

00:44:24.780 --> 00:44:29.500
of oil from Baku by summer 1920
and it's coming up the Volga

00:44:29.500 --> 00:44:33.250
and they're starting to make,
they're starting to refigure

00:44:33.250 --> 00:44:37.220
and redo some of the locomotives
that could only use wood.

00:44:37.220 --> 00:44:40.590
And they're starting to see
tremendous advantages from that.

00:44:40.590 --> 00:44:42.690
They're not really getting
Donetsk coal and I've included

00:44:42.690 --> 00:44:47.960
in the document in the handout
that shows as late as October 1920,

00:44:47.960 --> 00:44:51.790
only a 10th of the mine
workers that were working

00:44:51.790 --> 00:44:56.730
in the Donetsk coal basin
before World War 1 were employed

00:44:56.730 --> 00:44:58.030
at that time.

00:44:58.030 --> 00:44:59.690
So the maximum amount
that it produced was 1/10.

00:44:59.690 --> 00:45:03.500
There was a tremendous amount
of chaos and economic anarchy

00:45:03.500 --> 00:45:07.800
in the Ukraine, a lot of
fighting back and forth.

00:45:07.800 --> 00:45:12.390
When the Pols did attack in
April, May 1920 they got very far

00:45:12.390 --> 00:45:15.770 position:56%
into Ukraine, they actually captured
Kiev, they didn't get that far.

00:45:15.770 --> 00:45:21.410
Stalin was in the Ukraine for most
of 1920 and his goal was to try

00:45:21.410 --> 00:45:23.900
to restore the coal
industry in the Ukraine.

00:45:23.900 --> 00:45:26.630
When the Pols attacked
his focus was much more

00:45:26.630 --> 00:45:28.960
on the military side of things.

00:45:28.960 --> 00:45:34.300 position:56%
So what I wanted to just talk about
briefly and this is what I think one

00:45:34.300 --> 00:45:37.260
of the key things I got out of all
the primary source documents I used

00:45:37.260 --> 00:45:41.290
here I do think the documents at
the Hoover are very important,

00:45:41.290 --> 00:45:45.370
the things I got in the Soviet
archives are very important too is

00:45:45.370 --> 00:45:51.850 position:56%
that there were three key government
bodies throughout the course of 1920

00:45:51.850 --> 00:45:55.980
that made policy, debated
policy, etcetera, etcetera.

00:45:55.980 --> 00:46:00.970
And those were basically the
Soviet hierarchy, the senior part

00:46:00.970 --> 00:46:02.880
of that was the Council
Peoples Commissars.

00:46:02.880 --> 00:46:05.140
Lenin was chairman of the
Council Peoples Commissar,

00:46:05.140 --> 00:46:09.400
so under Council People Commissar
you had the commissar of transport,

00:46:09.400 --> 00:46:12.890
you had the commissar of the
food supply, etcetera, etcetera.

00:46:12.890 --> 00:46:14.720
And then obviously you
had the Communist Party

00:46:14.720 --> 00:46:16.510
and there was a Politburo.

00:46:16.510 --> 00:46:21.480
The Politburo really
made overarching general

00:46:21.480 --> 00:46:22.780
policy decisions.

00:46:22.780 --> 00:46:25.880
So when the Pols attacked for
instance questions about how

00:46:25.880 --> 00:46:28.860
that attack should be handled
in general terms were decided

00:46:28.860 --> 00:46:31.940
by the Politburo, but the Politburo
really didn't do a lot more

00:46:31.940 --> 00:46:33.330
than that.

00:46:33.330 --> 00:46:35.190
The key institution and when I was

00:46:35.190 --> 00:46:39.370
at Columbia this was [inaudible]
always suggests, always emphasized

00:46:39.370 --> 00:46:43.610 position:56%
to me is that if you can get a hold
of kind of the institutional history

00:46:43.610 --> 00:46:46.280
of what was going on
you can really kind

00:46:46.280 --> 00:46:49.750
of almost decode the most
important things after that.

00:46:49.750 --> 00:46:54.130
And what happens in early February,
although it's going this direction

00:46:54.130 --> 00:46:56.250
in January at the time of
the speech that I referred

00:46:56.250 --> 00:47:05.020
to is Lenin reinforces what was
previously called the Council

00:47:05.020 --> 00:47:06.320
of Defense.

00:47:06.320 --> 00:47:11.770
The Council of Defense coordinated
all defensive industrial activity

00:47:11.770 --> 00:47:17.110 position:56%
as the Red Army fought the white
armies really up until October 1919.

00:47:17.110 --> 00:47:20.730
And what Lenin and Trotsky decide
and this is as much Trotsky

00:47:20.730 --> 00:47:24.760
as Lenin is they decide that
the council of defense has

00:47:24.760 --> 00:47:28.840
to be expanded and it's renamed
the Council of Labor and Defense.

00:47:28.840 --> 00:47:31.960
And so what happens
during the course of 1920

00:47:31.960 --> 00:47:35.980
and there's a very good book that
goes into the research of this,

00:47:35.980 --> 00:47:39.560
it's the translation of English,
there's an English translation.

00:47:39.560 --> 00:47:42.420
It's documents from the Hoover
Institution called the Origin

00:47:42.420 --> 00:47:45.450
of Forced Labor in the
Soviet State 1917-1921

00:47:45.450 --> 00:47:49.530
if you just want to pass it around.

00:47:49.530 --> 00:47:53.620
The Council of Labor and Defense
actually becomes the key central

00:47:53.620 --> 00:47:58.390
economic organ to deal with
this mess that I've described,

00:47:58.390 --> 00:48:03.150
the transport system, lack of
food, the demographic issues

00:48:03.150 --> 00:48:07.130
of workers running away from
the main industrial centers

00:48:07.130 --> 00:48:10.880
and then factories are not open.

00:48:10.880 --> 00:48:15.900
Rykov sites the fact that there
are probably 3,300 factories

00:48:15.900 --> 00:48:17.730
under Soviet control.

00:48:17.730 --> 00:48:21.030
He says that over 1,800
them are closed,

00:48:21.030 --> 00:48:22.910
there's no one working there.

00:48:22.910 --> 00:48:24.210
They're barred, they're shut.

00:48:24.210 --> 00:48:27.010
That's because workers have
run away, they can't be fed,

00:48:27.010 --> 00:48:29.360
if they can't be fed
they're not going to work.

00:48:29.360 --> 00:48:32.880
And the regime can't provide them
enough food to stay there and work.

00:48:32.880 --> 00:48:38.430
It's really incredible the
whole speech and analysis

00:48:38.430 --> 00:48:41.710
by Rykov on January 25th, 1920.

00:48:41.710 --> 00:48:44.810
And so what happens is
the Council of Labor

00:48:44.810 --> 00:48:49.020
and Defense becomes the
central economic planning organ

00:48:49.020 --> 00:48:52.340
and it's really through the
Council of Labor and Defense

00:48:52.340 --> 00:48:59.180
that Trotsky organizes this effort
to retool and repair locomotives.

00:48:59.180 --> 00:49:02.730
If you want to accept the
number 3,800 in January 1920

00:49:02.730 --> 00:49:05.720
and they're going down 200 a month.

00:49:05.720 --> 00:49:09.820
That gets turned around through
Trotsky's efforts as minister

00:49:09.820 --> 00:49:11.200
of transport and then working

00:49:11.200 --> 00:49:13.090
through the Council
of Labor and Defense.

00:49:13.090 --> 00:49:16.410
And the reason the Council of Labor
and Defense is so important is

00:49:16.410 --> 00:49:21.680
that it also organized conscript
labor, especially peasant labor

00:49:21.680 --> 00:49:24.690
to go chop the wood
and transport it.

00:49:24.690 --> 00:49:31.680 position:56%
And the main interaction between the
Soviet state and the vast majority

00:49:31.680 --> 00:49:35.620
of the Russian population, which
was the peasantry was getting them

00:49:35.620 --> 00:49:40.930
to do conscript labor to
get wood because otherwise,

00:49:40.930 --> 00:49:43.330
you didn't have a transport system.

00:49:43.330 --> 00:49:49.130
So I wanted to wrap up
by saying that a lot

00:49:49.130 --> 00:49:55.000
of Trotsky's political career
was tied up with this whole idea

00:49:55.000 --> 00:50:03.860
of conscripting the peasantry to
go chop this wood and cart it,

00:50:03.860 --> 00:50:05.810
that's what they were doing.

00:50:05.810 --> 00:50:10.580 position:56%
There were limitations on how much
the regime could enforce that, very,

00:50:10.580 --> 00:50:15.200
very serious limitations because
it didn't have enough food

00:50:15.200 --> 00:50:17.730
to have Red Army soldiers do it.

00:50:17.730 --> 00:50:20.220
Red Army soldiers were now
conscripted on a regular basis

00:50:20.220 --> 00:50:22.690
to perform labor obligations.

00:50:22.690 --> 00:50:27.360
The reason that the peasantry was
particularly an inviting target was

00:50:27.360 --> 00:50:28.660
the peasants were told

00:50:28.660 --> 00:50:31.850
if you perform your labor
obligations you bring your own

00:50:31.850 --> 00:50:34.880
bread, we don't have to supply
it, but then we'll let you go.

00:50:34.880 --> 00:50:38.620
That is just the reality of
what happened during 1920.

00:50:38.620 --> 00:50:42.410
The story with the industrial
labor force in the major factories

00:50:42.410 --> 00:50:46.740
where they need to produce
spare parts for the railroads is

00:50:46.740 --> 00:50:51.570
and I have some information taken
from 1920 contemporary numbers,

00:50:51.570 --> 00:50:54.830
how much food were
these workers getting.

00:50:54.830 --> 00:51:00.510 position:56%
On average it was something like 15
to maybe 20 pounds of bread a month.

00:51:00.510 --> 00:51:04.060
That is not enough to perform
heavy industrial labor.

00:51:04.060 --> 00:51:08.150
And I think the most thing
point about the whole chaos

00:51:08.150 --> 00:51:12.200 position:56%
and just the whole fluidity of the
situation throughout 1920 and beyond

00:51:12.200 --> 00:51:15.230
because as I said, wood
remained the main source

00:51:15.230 --> 00:51:19.410
for fueling the Soviet
transport system long after 1920,

00:51:19.410 --> 00:51:21.670
long into the new economic policy

00:51:21.670 --> 00:51:24.480
when the food supply
dictatorship ended.

00:51:24.480 --> 00:51:28.780
Was that these factories
were not given enough food

00:51:28.780 --> 00:51:33.890
and I cite statistics from
these primary source documents.

00:51:33.890 --> 00:51:36.890
Some of the major factories that
were trying to produce spare parts

00:51:36.890 --> 00:51:42.380
or build new Soviet locomotives a
lot of them were fulfilling no more

00:51:42.380 --> 00:51:46.330
than 10% of the orders that
they were asked to fulfill.

00:51:46.330 --> 00:51:51.270
There was one factory in the
course of a month produced .9%

00:51:51.270 --> 00:51:56.090
of what Trotsky wanted
under order number 1042.

00:51:56.090 --> 00:52:01.330 position:56%
And so what you see is tremendous
numbers of workers being encouraged,

00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:06.290
invited, cajoled to come back
to the factories where they were

00:52:06.290 --> 00:52:09.240
with the promise that
they will be fed.

00:52:09.240 --> 00:52:13.450
And they're fed for a while and
then food supply deliveries,

00:52:13.450 --> 00:52:15.730
whatever reason don't work out.

00:52:15.730 --> 00:52:20.280 position:56%
And so there was approximately 100%
labor turnover throughout the course

00:52:20.280 --> 00:52:23.710
of 1920 and there's a lot of
very good information about this,

00:52:23.710 --> 00:52:27.050
even if it isn't exact it's
close enough to give you a sense

00:52:27.050 --> 00:52:28.830
of the fluidity of the situation.

00:52:28.830 --> 00:52:31.830
But how do you make this work if
you're in control of the regime,

00:52:31.830 --> 00:52:36.000
how do you do this if you're Lenin
and you stop governing bodies.

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:40.030
And the labor turnover for
just the second half of 1920

00:52:40.030 --> 00:52:43.090
after they started to get some oil,
a little bit of coal starts to come

00:52:43.090 --> 00:52:48.460
from the Ukraine, it was 60% just
during the last six months of 1920.

00:52:48.460 --> 00:52:52.080
So I think I ought to wrap
it up here it's been an hour.

00:52:52.080 --> 00:52:54.150
There's a lot more that I could
say, I would have liked to say more

00:52:54.150 --> 00:52:57.700
about Trotsky's role in
this, but I've got to be.

00:52:57.700 --> 00:52:59.180
&gt;&gt; Grant Harris: Five
more minutes if you need.

00:52:59.180 --> 00:53:01.310
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Kapiloff: Okay,
thank you very much Grant.

00:53:01.310 --> 00:53:08.470 position:56%
So I guess what I wanted to say is
if you compare the initial situation

00:53:08.470 --> 00:53:12.570
as of January 25th, 1920 when
Rykov gives this speech and talks

00:53:12.570 --> 00:53:14.550
about there's a separate
bureau [inaudible]

00:53:14.550 --> 00:53:18.450
and there's a separate
economy in the Ukraine,

00:53:18.450 --> 00:53:22.410
you've got central European Russia
kind of surviving on its own

00:53:22.410 --> 00:53:29.170
and most of it if it isn't a net
grain deficit situation it's just

00:53:29.170 --> 00:53:33.750
barely producing enough
food to feed itself.

00:53:33.750 --> 00:53:38.400 position:56%
What you see is during the course of
1920 a very, very concerted effort

00:53:38.400 --> 00:53:43.050
to start trying to stitch all
of these pieces back together.

00:53:43.050 --> 00:53:47.490
And what I can say is that by the
end of 1920 the progress was very,

00:53:47.490 --> 00:53:52.390
very limited, very, very limited
partly because the coal industry

00:53:52.390 --> 00:53:58.950
in the Ukraine had really
made any significant progress.

00:53:58.950 --> 00:54:03.750
There was a key document, you know,
Trotsky brought all of his papers

00:54:03.750 --> 00:54:09.220 position:56%
with him when he was sent into exile
by Stalin and they've been donated

00:54:09.220 --> 00:54:13.440
to the Harvard University, there's
the Trotsky archive at Harvard.

00:54:13.440 --> 00:54:16.010
And so there's a key
document in there,

00:54:16.010 --> 00:54:19.240 position:56%
I believe it's dated early November.

00:54:19.240 --> 00:54:20.710
Thank you.

00:54:20.710 --> 00:54:23.480
And he talks about the
fact that the coal industry

00:54:23.480 --> 00:54:27.970
in the Donetsk basin still isn't
working at the end of 1920.

00:54:27.970 --> 00:54:31.840
You do see some real progress
in the [inaudible] by the end

00:54:31.840 --> 00:54:34.990
of 1920 compared to
where it was in January.

00:54:34.990 --> 00:54:38.040 position:56%
And by the way, the first labor
army are created in the [inaudible].

00:54:38.040 --> 00:54:40.780
The [inaudible] is
basically Trotsky's,

00:54:40.780 --> 00:54:43.010
I don't want to call it
province, but it's his area.

00:54:43.010 --> 00:54:46.370
His people are in control there,
they're the ones that are trying

00:54:46.370 --> 00:54:51.370
to reestablish [inaudible] metal
industry, the coal industry

00:54:51.370 --> 00:54:53.420
in the [inaudible] and so forth.

00:54:53.420 --> 00:54:55.620
And what's very, very
interesting again,

00:54:55.620 --> 00:54:58.920
the primary source material
is really almost overwhelming,

00:54:58.920 --> 00:55:00.220
is that the Supreme Council

00:55:00.220 --> 00:55:03.150
of the National Economy despite
its name did not run the economy.

00:55:03.150 --> 00:55:07.030
It was just basically the
commissar of heavy industry.

00:55:07.030 --> 00:55:11.610
And what you see is all
this territory is recaptured

00:55:11.610 --> 00:55:14.790
by the Soviet Regime and
eventually Siberia as well,

00:55:14.790 --> 00:55:18.500
within the Supreme Council of the
National Economy there are four

00:55:18.500 --> 00:55:20.370
or five separate divisions.

00:55:20.370 --> 00:55:24.760
So there is basically a
division that controls industry

00:55:24.760 --> 00:55:29.270
in European Russia
and that is separate

00:55:29.270 --> 00:55:32.640
and Rykov runs it,
he's the chairman.

00:55:32.640 --> 00:55:35.530
But there's a separate,
a whole separate division

00:55:35.530 --> 00:55:38.490
of the Supreme Council of the
National Economy just for Ukraine

00:55:38.490 --> 00:55:43.690
and it has no interaction
with the Central European one.

00:55:43.690 --> 00:55:48.340 position:56%
And then down here where the Cossack
area is there is a separate Supreme

00:55:48.340 --> 00:55:52.050
Council of the National
Economy for Southeast Russia

00:55:52.050 --> 00:55:53.600
and there's a separate
one for the [inaudible]

00:55:53.600 --> 00:55:55.590
and then finally one for Siberia.

00:55:55.590 --> 00:55:58.560
That is still the case
at the end of 1920.

00:55:58.560 --> 00:56:01.750
So there is some progress
made, but it's very limited

00:56:01.750 --> 00:56:06.980 position:56%
and I will end here now by saying
that this key monograph that I found

00:56:06.980 --> 00:56:13.220
that was published in 1922 it looks
back at the end of 1920 and 1921.

00:56:13.220 --> 00:56:17.500
And basically what it says is
that with the limited resources

00:56:17.500 --> 00:56:19.390
that the regime had it
started to get some oil,

00:56:19.390 --> 00:56:22.930 position:56%
it started to get a little bit of
coal, coal also from the [inaudible]

00:56:22.930 --> 00:56:27.200
that the geographic
dimensions of the area

00:56:27.200 --> 00:56:30.690
that the regime was controlling
overwhelmed the resource,

00:56:30.690 --> 00:56:33.000
even the limited resource it could
bring to bear when it started

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:37.280
to get oil and coal that simply
the Ukraine remained separate

00:56:37.280 --> 00:56:39.570
from European Russia.

00:56:39.570 --> 00:56:43.050 position:56%
The [inaudible] and Siberia remained
separate from European Russia.

00:56:43.050 --> 00:56:48.670 position:56%
And I do believe that that
underlying economic crisis had a lot

00:56:48.670 --> 00:56:52.350
to do, not just the issue
about food, had a lot to do

00:56:52.350 --> 00:56:55.630
with the recognition by
Lenin and say the government

00:56:55.630 --> 00:56:59.780 position:56%
that they really had to make a major
change and that had a lot to do

00:56:59.780 --> 00:57:04.900
with why the new economic policy
was declared in the spring of 1921.

00:57:04.900 --> 00:57:07.470 position:56%
There are obviously other reasons
we know about the [inaudible] revolt

00:57:07.470 --> 00:57:11.850
and a lot of sailors and workers
were revolting against the regime.

00:57:11.850 --> 00:57:15.500
But if you look at the real
underlying economic reality

00:57:15.500 --> 00:57:20.550
of where things stood by 1920 and
the limited progress that was made

00:57:20.550 --> 00:57:25.850 position:56%
by the end of 1921 in effect the
regime did not control the territory

00:57:25.850 --> 00:57:29.080
it had won from the
white armies, it did not.

00:57:29.080 --> 00:57:34.060 position:56%
It did several years later, but this
was a tremendously difficult process

00:57:34.060 --> 00:57:39.180
and it was a wood economy that
took the entire country back more

00:57:39.180 --> 00:57:40.480
than 50 years.

00:57:40.480 --> 00:57:42.560
So I'm going to end there.

00:57:42.560 --> 00:57:45.330
