00:58:00.340 --> 00:58:05.300
&gt;&gt; So what about I guess within
Soviet Union in terms of trade,

00:58:05.300 --> 00:58:09.030
did they trade for oil,
[inaudible] like Southeast Asia or?

00:58:09.030 --> 00:58:13.300
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Kapiloff: Okay, yeah
so I want to answer your question,

00:58:13.300 --> 00:58:18.440
but let me just you a little bit of
background about what was going on.

00:58:18.440 --> 00:58:23.950
So obviously one of the things
I didn't mention was during most

00:58:23.950 --> 00:58:25.320
of the Civil War period, certainly

00:58:25.320 --> 00:58:30.590
through 1919 there was a major
trade embargo the Western European

00:58:30.590 --> 00:58:35.020
countries that Lenin referred to
as the top powers refused to trade

00:58:35.020 --> 00:58:39.080
because they were actively
supporting the white armies.

00:58:39.080 --> 00:58:41.300
And there's a lot of talk

00:58:41.300 --> 00:58:43.820
about there was some
British soldiers dropped off

00:58:43.820 --> 00:58:48.380
up here near the Donetsk area
and [inaudible] maybe was 600.

00:58:48.380 --> 00:58:51.990
The real ally contribution
to the white cause was

00:58:51.990 --> 00:58:57.880
that the armaments given bullets,
machine guns, and everything a lot

00:58:57.880 --> 00:59:02.420
of good economic work has been
done equaled the entire production

00:59:02.420 --> 00:59:05.740
of what the limited Soviet
arms industry could produce

00:59:05.740 --> 00:59:07.040
with the Red Army.

00:59:07.040 --> 00:59:09.010
It was a major, major contribution.

00:59:09.010 --> 00:59:16.000
That embargo ended in January
1920, it's reported, you know,

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:19.540
in big bold letters in Pravda and
Izvestia and it's very important.

00:59:19.540 --> 00:59:24.470
The reality was that there
was no real trade until later.

00:59:24.470 --> 00:59:29.220
But what happens in January,
February, March 1920 and I do want

00:59:29.220 --> 00:59:34.270
to answer your specific
question is Trotsky's predecessor

00:59:34.270 --> 00:59:35.760
of the commissar of transport,

00:59:35.760 --> 00:59:39.990
a very skilled engineer named
Krassen [phonetic] goes to England

00:59:39.990 --> 00:59:42.800
because the idea is he wants
to start buying locomotives

00:59:42.800 --> 00:59:44.480
and there's a Soviet trade
delegation [inaudible]

00:59:44.480 --> 00:59:46.360
into Western Europe.

00:59:46.360 --> 00:59:48.620
There are a lot of things
the Soviet economy needs

00:59:48.620 --> 00:59:53.000
or I would say the European Russian
economy under Soviet control needs.

00:59:53.000 --> 00:59:56.630
They need a lot of things, they
need grain, they need many things.

00:59:56.630 --> 01:00:00.650
The only thing that Krassen is
trying to get is locomotives.

01:00:00.650 --> 01:00:04.270
And Trotsky says in some of his
key speeches in his collected works

01:00:04.270 --> 01:00:05.580
and they're really remarkable.

01:00:05.580 --> 01:00:09.430
I can just tell you the notes just
in that volume have information

01:00:09.430 --> 01:00:11.320
that you won't find any place else.

01:00:11.320 --> 01:00:14.170
But basically Trotsky says we won't
be able to get any locomotives.

01:00:14.170 --> 01:00:19.970
And in terms of oil
what happened is when --

01:00:19.970 --> 01:00:21.780
this is why the regime
got very lucky

01:00:21.780 --> 01:00:25.540
and I should have mentioned this
and I want to get to your question.

01:00:25.540 --> 01:00:30.800
When the Red Army captured
Baku the big deal was

01:00:30.800 --> 01:00:33.010
that there were 200
million poods of oil

01:00:33.010 --> 01:00:34.530
that had already been
taken out of the ground.

01:00:34.530 --> 01:00:36.210
I don't know if they were
literally in barrels,

01:00:36.210 --> 01:00:38.200
but they were ready to be shipped.

01:00:38.200 --> 01:00:40.940
And there had been a lot
of destruction to some

01:00:40.940 --> 01:00:44.480
of the oil infrastructure in Baku.

01:00:44.480 --> 01:00:48.690
And so before 1914 Baku have
seen a lot of information.

01:00:48.690 --> 01:00:51.240
Trotsky writes about it,
Trotsky is an incredible writer

01:00:51.240 --> 01:00:55.740
and not just flowerily, but he
talks about things in great detail.

01:00:55.740 --> 01:00:59.000
He's of incredible use
to anyone who wants

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:01.050
to seriously study this period.

01:01:01.050 --> 01:01:03.990
And so up to 35 million poods

01:01:03.990 --> 01:01:06.860
of oil is being produced a
month in Baku before the war.

01:01:06.860 --> 01:01:11.050
When the Red Army captures it
it's only 10 to 15 million.

01:01:11.050 --> 01:01:16.380
But the 200 million that's there
allows them to start using it.

01:01:16.380 --> 01:01:19.170
And there's even talk that
given how much they need to use

01:01:19.170 --> 01:01:23.330
if they can transport it that
they're going to run out by 1922.

01:01:23.330 --> 01:01:26.390
And I'm sure we all have
recognized the name Arm and Hammer.

01:01:26.390 --> 01:01:31.150
It was Arm and hammer that helped
the Soviet Union restore this.

01:01:31.150 --> 01:01:36.310
And so in terms of trade I can't, I
would think that there's a lot more

01:01:36.310 --> 01:01:38.850
in The Prize by Daniel Yergin

01:01:38.850 --> 01:01:42.400
and about how much
oil if any was traded.

01:01:42.400 --> 01:01:44.450
But basically what you
have by the beginning

01:01:44.450 --> 01:01:46.670
of 1920 is the effective
end of the embargo,

01:01:46.670 --> 01:01:51.920
although there was no real
trade until late 1920.

01:01:51.920 --> 01:01:54.580
Then there was talk of trade
with the Western countries.

01:01:54.580 --> 01:02:00.630
And one of the main things that
the regime had to trade was wood

01:02:00.630 --> 01:02:03.580
from the far northwest,
from the far --

01:02:03.580 --> 01:02:07.770
that's one of the main things that
they thought they could trade.

01:02:07.770 --> 01:02:12.060
Because the wood resources of
European Russia not even talking

01:02:12.060 --> 01:02:16.780
about Siberia they're more than
a third of all the forestry

01:02:16.780 --> 01:02:19.860
in the world at the time
going back to that time.

01:02:19.860 --> 01:02:24.160
So just to repeat your question
again, there is some trade.

01:02:24.160 --> 01:02:27.720
I think that the regime
needed whatever oil it had.

01:02:27.720 --> 01:02:29.030
I don't know if it traded any oil.

01:02:29.030 --> 01:02:32.190
One of the things that was very
interesting that they were trying

01:02:32.190 --> 01:02:36.220
to trade and it gives you
a sense of how special.

01:02:36.220 --> 01:02:41.850
Siberia was a tremendous producer
of very high quality butter

01:02:41.850 --> 01:02:46.810 position:56%
and so there was a tremendous amount
of butter exported from Siberia

01:02:46.810 --> 01:02:49.130
for instance to England
Western Europe.

01:02:49.130 --> 01:02:52.320
And so that was one of the things
they were looking at trading wood,

01:02:52.320 --> 01:02:55.110
butter, those were
the two main things.

01:02:55.110 --> 01:02:57.380
I believe they wanted
to hold on to the oil,

01:02:57.380 --> 01:02:59.930
but there were other things
they needed technology.

01:02:59.930 --> 01:03:06.100
You see during this period that the
entire telegraphic system becomes

01:03:06.100 --> 01:03:07.440
totally unreliable.

01:03:07.440 --> 01:03:10.600
